Using the Missingno package we can visualize the missing values in each column and rows. This gives us a clear estimate of which column to keep and which to remove.

Observations from missing values:¶

calendar.csv¶

  • As we can observe for calendar.csv the price column has a significant amount of missing values, and luckily in this case the way to deal with these missing values are quite simple.
  • The missing values in price column is directly related to the false values in the availability column.
  • This means that when the dates for which the listings are not available the price is nan, this can be due to the fact that the listings are either already booked or are under maintance. And since the latter is a rare occurance so we will assume that the former is the case.

listings.csv¶

  • As we can observe for listings.csv the missing values are really negligible, so even if we drop the rows for the missing values we wont incur much loss.

Step 2.1 & 2.2 : Data prep and analysis for calendar.csv¶

We modify the calendar dataframe to add new column for month and weekday for that particular date. This will help us analyze whether there is some pattern for the availibility of the listings with respect to the day of the week and month

Observations from calendar.csv :¶

  • The rate of availability varies by some amount when compared with repect to month of the year but not with respect to the days of the week.
  • The price rates varies for both day of the week and month of the year.
  • The rate of availability can vary due to two reasons:
    • The listing is already booked
    • The listing is down for repair
    • The second reason is rare and will not show any significant change in the patterns.
    • So we will assume that all of the times when listing is not availabe it is because they are already occupied.
  • From the variation in the rate of availability with respect to the month we can observe the following things:
    • The listings are occupied the most during the months (In descending order):
      • january
      • july
      • august
    • The listings are occupied the least during the months (In descending order):
      • December
      • November
      • March

  • From the variation in the price with respect to the month we can observe the following things:

    • The listings are priced highest during the months (In descending order):
      • July
      • August
      • June
    • The listings are priced lowest during the months (In descending order):
      • January
      • February
      • March

  • From the above observations we can infer the following things:

What is the best month to visit seattle if you are on a budget?

- January, February and March are months where the price rates are the lowest. Especially in january and that is the reason most of the listings are occupied in January. And the listings are relatively less occupied in february and march because the prices rates starts increasing again. 
- So if people want to enjoy their time in seattle with a slightly less cold weather but still fairly cheap prices February and march is a good time to book an airbnb.

From owners POV what is the best time to list your propery on Airbnb? And how to set price rates according to the time of the year?

- On the other hand the summers especially in the month of July, August and June the price rates are the heighest because it is a comfortable weather and that is when most of the tourists come and visit seattle.
- So from a buissness point of view if you are planning to list your property on airbnb and want to maximize your profits you should set your prices high during the summer season as the volume of tourist are already very high and most of the hotels will already be fully booked so there are chances that people would be willing to pay high amount of money to find a place to stay. On the other hand january is the month when you should set your prices to be budget friendly because that is what will attract people to book your listing in that cold weather.

What is the best time in year when owners can take down their listing for maintainance and repair?

- From owners point of view the best months to get the listings repaired without incurring a major loss would be in the month of November and December.

In [40]:
def assign_census_tract(bnb):
    ''' creates a bools list which is a lists that 
    consists of boolean values for the census tracts that the
    latitude and longitude point lies in.
    
    Attributes:
        bnb: The dataframe on which we want to get the bools list.
        
    Returns:
        nan value if there is none of the values are True in the bools list.
        else returns list containing the census tract types for the element 
        in the dataframe.
    '''
    bools = [geom.contains(bnb['geometry']) for geom in seattle['geometry']]
    if True in bools:
        return seattle.iloc[bools.index(True)]['NAMELSAD10']
    else:
        return np.nan

def choropleth(col):
    '''Creates a chloropleth plot which tells about the density of the col(it can be any float or integer col
    in our case its the BNBs, BNB_density and price column)'''
    f = plt.figure(figsize=(30, 20))
    ax = f.gca()
    kw = dict(column=col, k=6, cmap='YlGn', alpha=1, legend=True, edgecolor='gray', linewidth=0.5)
    seattle.plot(scheme='QUANTILES', ax=ax, **kw)
    seattle.apply(lambda x: ax.annotate(fontsize= 7, s=x['NAMELSAD10'], xy=x.geometry.centroid.coords[0], ha='center'), axis=1);
    ax.set_axis_off()
In [102]:
choropleth('BNBs')

There is one fault in the above plot, that is the bigger the area the more bnbs will be there in that tract, which does not give a fiar measure of how BNB dense the tract is instead we need to calculate the density of the BNB's in the tract.

In [103]:
seattle['BNBDensity'] = (seattle['BNBs'] / seattle['geometry']\
                            .to_crs({'init': 'epsg:3395'})\
                            .map(lambda p: p.area / 10**6))\
                            .fillna(0)

Scatter plot for visualizing the density of the types of airbnbs in different regions of seattle¶

In [77]:
def plot_scatter(col, type = ''):
    '''Plots a scatter plot on the seattle map.
    the size of the points in the scatter plot is dependent on the 
    price of the listings. 
    
    Attributes:
        col: column that we want to visualize on the seattle map,
        it can be property_type, bedrooms, accomodates column
        type: For the given column we can visualize any particular
        value. eg. for property_type column we can visualize where 
        the apartments are in seattle
    '''
        
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(25, 16))
    sample = listings_pd_ppl_nonan.sample(1500)
    colors = np.random.rand(len(listings_pd_ppl_nonan[col].unique()))
    base = seattle.plot(ax=ax, alpha=0.4, linewidth=0.25, color='grey')
    sns.kdeplot(data=listings_pd_ppl_nonan.apply(lambda srs: pd.Series({'x': srs.geometry.x, 'y': srs.geometry.y}), axis='columns'), ax=ax,
            alpha=1)
    if type == '':
        for i in listings_pd_ppl_nonan[col].unique():
            x_cor = sample[sample[col]==i].geometry.x
            y_cor = sample[sample[col]==i].geometry.y
            ax.scatter(x_cor,y_cor,label=i, s = sample['price'],alpha=0.5)
    else:
        x_cor = sample[sample[col]==type].geometry.x
        y_cor = sample[sample[col]==type].geometry.y
        ax.scatter(x_cor,y_cor,label=type, c= colors, s = sample['price'],alpha=0.5)

    ax.legend()
    ax.set_axis_off()

Inferences from listings.csv:¶

From the above observations we can answer some pretty interesting buissness questions, here are some of them:¶

What are some patterns observed from the data that might help increase the business of airbnb owners? First point:

  • First lets clear out the misconception, that most of the people might have. That is, the more densly populated the area might be the more competitive the prices are. And vice versa. But that is not the case here. The densly populated areas that is the main city area and some other areas such as the outskirts of Seattle are packed with BNB's but land up at the top of the average price list. And some less dense areas or tracts have very affordable prices.
  • This can be better explained using the concept of supply demand. To a normal person or an inexperienced eye it would appear that the supply in the high BNB density tracts or the main city area would seem to be pretty high and somehow more then the demand, that way the price rate for each bnb would be really competetive to attract the tourists. But in reality the supply is still pretty less in comparison to the demand and due to that the BNB owners in the BNB dense areas can get away with above average prices and still have people booking their listings. Where as the demand in the less dense BNB tracts its the complete opposite, and the BNB owners have to set competetive prices and fight for the customers.
  • So if you are planning to get into real estate and Airbnb buisness curate some cash and buy some apartments or houses in the main city or BNB dense areas that way you would'nt have to care as much about the price rates of your listings and still maximize your profits to a certain extent.

Second point:

  • From the accomodates scatter plot we can observe that major of the airbnbs are catering young bachelors or couples. This can be observed from the huge number of appartments or houses that only accomodate only 2 or 4 peoples all over seattle. And due to same reason major BNB's are 1 bedroom listings.This can be justified by the age distribution in seattle, major population being young bachelors or young couples. That is why major BNB listings are setup in a way to cater the larger percent of the age distribution.
  • So apart from the above suggestions another way to maximize your earnings would be to cater the larger population. To be specific it would be better to have multiple 1 or 2 bedroom apartments instead of a big apartment. And even if you have a bigger property say 4 bedroom apartment or a house it would be prefered to list each room of the property as a seperate listing.
